## 3. Acceptance Criteria

Tags: **[v1]** = in the first shippable version · **[later]** = deferred to a later phase.
Form: `AC-N: Given … When … Then …` (observable, testable).

### R1 — Build (generate + instrument)
- **AC-1 [v1]:** Given a content brief, When the user runs the build skill, Then the system
  produces an interactive HTML draft saved as `_v0.html` in the document workspace.
- **AC-2 [v1]:** Given a generated or supplied HTML draft, When it is prepared for review,
  Then every reviewable block carries a unique `data-wid` of the form `{slide}-{role}-{ordinal}`,
  and no two elements share a `data-wid`.
- **AC-3 [v1]:** Given a draft is built, When it is opened, Then it renders in the browser via
  the React front end without the user issuing any further CLI command.
- **AC-4 [later]:** Given an existing externally-authored HTML file (AI-generated or
  wicked-prezzie output), When the user points the build skill at it, Then it is instrumented
  with `data-wid` IDs and enters the same review loop.

### R2 — In-browser feedback
- **AC-5 [v1]:** Given the draft is displayed, When the user hovers a reviewable block,
  Then that whole element is visibly outlined and selectable (block-level; arbitrary
  text-range selection is **[later]**).
- **AC-6 [v1]:** Given a block is selected, When the user opens the feedback control,
  Then they can attach a plain-language instruction and choose/confirm the edit `type`.
- **AC-7 [v1]:** Given one or more feedback items are attached, When the user views the page,
  Then a visible indicator shows which blocks have pending feedback and how many.

### R3 — UPDATE → versioned markdown
- **AC-8 [v1]:** Given pending feedback exists, When the user clicks **UPDATE**, Then a file
  `_v{x}.md` is written where `x` is the next integer in the chain, containing YAML frontmatter
  (`version`, `base_html`, `timestamp`) and one section per item with `selector` (data-wid),
  `type`, `instruction`, and `before` (original snapshot).
- **AC-9 [v1]:** Given an UPDATE is in progress, When the user clicks UPDATE again, Then the
  control is disabled until processing completes (no double-submit).
- **AC-10 [v1]:** Given a feedback item references a `data-wid` whose current content differs
  from its recorded `before`, When the file is processed, Then the stale item is flagged
  rather than silently applied.

### R4 — Monitor + regeneration
- **AC-11 [v1]:** Given a new `_v{x}.md` appears, When the monitor detects it, Then it produces
  `_v{x}.html` by reading the prior `_v{x-1}.html` and applying only the listed edits.
- **AC-12 [v1]:** Given a `content-edit` or `style-edit` item, When it is processed, Then the
  change is applied by deterministic DOM surgery (no LLM call) and only the targeted element
  changes.
- **AC-13 [v1]:** Given a `structural-change` item, When it is processed, Then only the serialized
  fragment of the targeted element is sent to the LLM, and the returned fragment is swapped back
  in place.
- **AC-14 [v1]:** Given any regeneration completes, When the output is written, Then the prior
  version file is left byte-unchanged on disk (write-once; never overwrite a `_vN`).

### R5 — Live loop
- **AC-15 [v1]:** Given a new `_v{x}.html` is produced, When the browser is showing the document,
  Then the displayed content updates to `_v{x}` within **2 seconds** for deterministic edits
  without a full page navigation.
- **AC-16 [v1]:** Given the page updates to a new version, When the swap occurs, Then the user's
  scroll position is preserved (within one viewport) and their in-progress annotation overlay
  is not lost.
- **AC-17 [v1]:** Given the monitor is processing, When regeneration has started but not finished,
  Then the UI shows a processing indicator within 500ms of UPDATE.

### R6 — Architecture / service
- **AC-18 [v1]:** Given a fresh session, When the user runs the single start command, Then one
  local service starts, serves the React app, watches the workspace, and opens the browser —
  with no further CLI interaction required for the rest of the session.
- **AC-19 [v1]:** Given the loop runs, When feedback is received, regeneration completes, and
  export is requested, Then the service emits `presentation.feedback.received`,
  `presentation.html.updated`, and `presentation.export.requested` events respectively to wicked-bus.

### R7 — Version navigation & reset
- **AC-20 [v1]:** Given a document with N versions, When the user views the page, Then a version
  navigation control lists all versions and lets the user move to any one (back/forward), with
  the current working head clearly indicated.
- **AC-21 [v1]:** Given the user is viewing version `vK` (K < head), When they choose "start again
  from here", Then `vK` is **forked** to a new head version; `vK` and all later versions remain on
  disk and navigable (non-destructive).
- **AC-22 [v1]:** Given any number of resets/forks have occurred, When the user navigates history,
  Then no previously-produced version is unreachable (the user can never get "lost").
- **AC-23 [v1]:** Given version metadata, When a version is created, Then it records its parent
  version, the feedback file that produced it, and a timestamp.

### R8 — Export
- **AC-24 [v1]:** Given the working head, When the user clicks "Export → HTML", Then a single
  self-contained `.html` file is produced with all JS, CSS, and assets inlined, which renders and
  retains its interactivity when opened directly from the filesystem (no server).
- **AC-25 [v1]:** Given the working head, When the user clicks "Export → PDF", Then a PDF is
  produced via wicked-prezzie's render/PDF primitives that visually matches the rendered draft.
- **AC-26 [v1]:** Given an export is requested, When it runs, Then it is triggered entirely from
  the browser UI (no CLI step) and the resulting file path is surfaced to the user.

